			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bards im the wolrd of Tolken.<a name="43653"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 2 04 10:13 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Words, songs, and nature are the sources of &quot;magical&quot; power in Tolkien's world.  (Galadriel chuckled at Sam's &quot;elf magic&quot; name for what was simply a natural thing for her.)  Frodo called upon Elbereth, both on weathertop and in Shelob's lair, and the very name had power.  Bombadil's songs and words carried power.  (A power that emanted from who he IS by nature:  A Maia, or angelic being).  
<br />

<br />
Same goes for Elves.  They ALL sing and recite verse, and to mortals especially, it is enchanting.  Sam describes the songs shared in Elrond's house as being &quot;inside a song&quot;.  The effect of the Elvish music was wholesome, rejuvenating, and encouraging.  But then, the very <i>presence</i> of Glorfindel (not Arwen) brought Frodo somewhat back from the shadow world before Glorfindel's horse raced him to the fords of Bruinnen (sp?).
<br />

<br />
ALL of Tolkien's magical beings are Bards, AND Druids.  Their &quot;power&quot; comes from who they are, and their oneness with nature, and their power is projected through words and/or song.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=564823">Scherzo Glissando </a><BR>
Maestro, Molto Espressivo</span></td>
